enth- and nineteenth-century celebrities shape key political concepts such as freedom, consent, contract, citizenship, and sovereignty. Whether analyzing Wheatley's fame in relation to conceptions of race and freedom, notions of consent in Hemings's relationship with Thomas Jefferson, or Baartman's ability to enter into legal contracts, Pinto reveals the centrality of race, gender, and sexuality in the formation of political rights. In so doing, she contends that feminist theories of black women's vulnerable embodiment can be the starting point for future progressive political projects.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican American feminists. 0aAfrican American women in popular culture. 0aAfrican American womenxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aFamexSocial aspects. 0aWomanism. 0aWomen, BlackxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aWomen, Black, in popular culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh2 aNational Endowment for the Humanitiesefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069631840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478093800?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478093800zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478093800/original  a978-3-11-069631-8 Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA